SIMPLE: judge-made
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Judge-made
<hw>Judge"-made`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Created by judges or judicial
decision; -- applied esp. to law applied or established by the judicial
interpretation of statutes so as extend or restrict their scope, as to
meet new cases, to provide new or better remedies, etc., and often used
opprobriously of acts of judicial interpretation considered as doing
this. <ex>Judge-made</ex> law is contrasted with <contr>statutory
law</contr> and <contr>civil law</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The law of the 13th century was <qex>judge-made</qex> law in a
fuller and more literal sense than the law of any succeeding century has
been.</q> <rj><qau>Sir Frederick Pollock.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Judger</ent>⟦br⟧
